Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.68) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.13. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.89 (S.E. = 1.92, p < .001, 95% CI [10.13, 17.65]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.03, p = 0.020, 95% CI [0.01, 0.15]; Std. beta = 0.30, 95% CI [0.05, 0.55])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.85, S.E. = 0.99, p = 0.391, 95% CI [-2.79, 1.09]; Std. beta = -0.22, 95% CI [-0.72, 0.28])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.69, S.E. = 0.79, p = 0.386, 95% CI [-2.24, 0.87]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.58, 0.22])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.62, S.E. = 1.18, p = 0.002, 95% CI [1.31, 5.93]; Std. beta = 0.94, 95% CI [0.34, 1.53])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
